Tomorrow, I defend the proposal for my dissertation. For now, the dissertation is tentatively titled: &ldquo;Scriptural, but Not Religious: Karl Barth, Dietrich Bonhoeffer, and a Biblical Critique of Religion.&rdquo;
Here&rsquo;s the &ldquo;elevator pitch&rdquo; for the dissertation. Feedback appreciated.
Scriptural, but Not Religious: Barth, Bonhoeffer, and a Biblical Critique of Religion My project traces its origins to a single classroom discussion question in the Spring of 2015. The question was this: &ldquo;In what ways is Bonhoeffer&rsquo;s understanding of religion similar to, and different from, that of Barth?

UPDATE: Read my post, &ldquo;Two More Pieces about Jordan Peterson.&rdquo;
If I remember correctly, I first heard of and listened to Jordan Peterson on an episode of The Art of Manliness podcast. (Or perhaps it was this episode.)
However, I could be mistaken, because Peterson&rsquo;s been popping up in conversation all over the place in my circles. Blog posts, podcast episodes, conversations with friends - Peterson has been popping up everywhere, so it seems.

Tim Challies begins his book, Do More Better: A Practical Guide to Productivity with a bold claim: &ldquo;I believe this book can improve your life.&rdquo;
However, after reading the book, which is just 120 pages long including endnotes!, I believe that Challies makes good on his claim.
As far as explicitly Christian approaches to personal productivity go, Challies’ Do More Better stands alongside Matt Perman’s What’s Best Next: How the Gospel Transforms the Way You Get Things Done.

Getting Things Done (&ldquo;GTD&rdquo; for short) is a wildly popular personal productivity system invented and popularized by David Allen. However, as Nicole Dieker at Lifehacker pointed out in 2017, &ldquo;You don’t hear a lot of people talk about the Getting Things Done productivity system anymore.&rdquo;
I think that&rsquo;s a shame, because it&rsquo;s a very effective system.
I first tried Getting Things Done after reading &quot; What&rsquo;s Best Nex t&quot; by Matt Perman, and then reading &quot; Getting Things Done&quot; by David Allen (in its newly revised 2015 edition) shortly thereafter.

[caption id=&quot;&quot; align=&ldquo;alignright&rdquo; width=&ldquo;300&rdquo;] Silent Cross by Margot Krebs Neale[/caption]
&ldquo;Violence is not human destiny because the God of peace is the beginning and the end of human history&hellip;
&ldquo;Granted, pushing the stone of peace up the steep hill of violence &hellip; is hard. It is easier, however, than carrying one&rsquo;s own cross in the footsteps of the crucified Messiah. This is what Jesus Christ asks Christians to do. Assured of God&rsquo;s justice and undergirded by God&rsquo;s presence, they are to break the cycle of violence by refusing to be caught in the automatism of revenge.

Rachel and I are in the middle of our second month of calling Birmingham, Alabama &ldquo;home.&rdquo;
While we could both do with a little less humidity (!), we&rsquo;re enjoying ourselves and our surroundings down here in Alabama.
What&rsquo;s Happening in Birmingham, AL: I don&rsquo;t start my M.Div. coursework at Beeson Divinity School until late August, but I&rsquo;ve already started working at Beeson&rsquo;s Media Center (follow our nascent Twitter account here). It&rsquo;s an incredibly convenient on-campus job.

